text:
if that seam making material on the roll is like the iron on patches for pants and such, its basically hot melt glue smeared out on the backing, maybe a bit porous in your case so it can melt and pass through to both sides and adhere both sides of the inside of the seam together, 

IE you could use a thin strip of hot melt glue on something covering both sides and then iron the cloth over it so it melts into the cloth and holds it together, or just run a seam of hot melt glue on the back of the edge and fold over then iron heat it up again as well as creasing or pressing the edge together 

something I am finding useful for this, is that the hot melt glue can be used to hold things much more steady than pins and can then be very easily sewn together even roughly by hand, which wil withstand higher temps of the sun baking the cloth, than the hot melt glue might, :) (my experience is with canvas for making tent segments with inbuilt thermal diode material for use both summer and winter times :)
